# Portfolio approach cpd

![](data:image/png;base64,)![](data:image/png;base64,)![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
The portfolio approach is a strategic management method that combines multiple initiatives into a cohesive and adaptable framework, aiming to achieve significant development impact.

## Purpose
The purpose of the portfolio approach is to maximize impact through collaborative efforts across different projects, promoting systemic thinking, conflict sensitivity, and responsible practices in research and development (R&D).

## How it works
The portfolio approach involves organizing projects into cohesive groups, enabling collaborative efforts, systemic thinking, conflict sensitivity, adaptability, accelerated impact, and intersectionality to address complex challenges effectively.

## Requirements
Effectively utilizing the portfolio approach for R&D requires a range of skills, including project management, collaboration, conflict resolution, and strategic planning. Access to relevant data, resources, and technology is also essential, along with clear communication channels and strong stakeholder engagement.

## Reflections
When employing the portfolio approach for R&D, it's crucial to maintain alignment with overarching objectives while embracing project diversity to address various facets of the research agenda. Resource allocation should be judiciously managed, and robust monitoring and evaluation mechanisms implemented to track progress and adapt as needed.

## Related methods (if any)
Co-creation, Design Thinking, system innovation

## Examples
The portfolio approach has been successfully applied in various contexts, including the United Nations Development Programme's (UNDP) Country Programme Document (CPD), where it was used to address complex development challenges and drive impactful results.
